","1337–1392":"1337–1392","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1288–Male":"1288–Overleden","1291–1344":"1291–1344","1372":"1372","1392":"1392","1291":"1291","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1288":"1288","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","about 1364":"circa 1364","1318":"1318","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ireland":"Ierland","Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ierland","Barrymore Castle, Cork, Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ierland"},"en":{"1320–1372":"1320–1372","1315–1344":"1315–1344","1318–1390":"1318–1390","1337–1392":"1337–1392","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1288–Male":"1288–Deceased","1291–1344":"1291–1344","1372":"1372","1392":"1392","1291":"1291","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1288":"1288","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","about 1364":"about 1364","1318":"1318","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Ireland":"Ireland","Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ireland","Barrymore Castle, Cork, Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Courcy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Andree, Jacques, Michel, Monique.","French: habitational name from any of the places in Calvados, Loiret, Manche, and Marne called Courcy.","History: Nicolas Lemière <i>dit</i> Courcy from Courcy in Manche, France, married Louise-Geneviève Dubé in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1749."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Courcy was born in 1320, in Cork, County Cork, Ireland, her father, Miles de Courcy 1st Baron Kingsale, was 32 and her mother, Joan de Cogan, was 29. She married Lord David Barry 6th Baron about 1364, in Cork, County Cork, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1372, in Ireland, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1320–1372":"1320–1372","1315–1344":"1315–1344","1318–1390":"1318–1390","1337–1392":"1337–1392","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1291–1344":"1291–1344","1372":"1372","1392":"1392","1291":"1291","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1288":"1288","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","about 1364":"umbes 1364","1318":"1318","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Iirimaa","Barrymore Castle, Cork, Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1320–1372":"1320–1372","1315–1344":"1315–1344","1318–1390":"1318–1390","1337–1392":"1337–1392","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1288–Male":"1288–Kuollut","1291–1344":"1291–1344","1372":"1372","1392":"1392","1291":"1291","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1288":"1288","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","about 1364":"noin 1364","1318":"1318","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ireland":"Irlanti","Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Irlanti","Barrymore Cast